Food to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation measured in the eurozone is the rapid rise in food prices.
Inflation in the 13 eurozone countries was higher than expected in November - an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded after the 2.6 percent in October, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are based on only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
In contrast to the US, British, and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the Leitzsins. At their discretion, the reduction in interest rates would favour the rise in commodity prices and the slight decline in unemployment in order to create an inflation spiral.
The ECB strives to keep the inflation rate below two percent, or at least close to the two-percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in a dilemma: it is necessary to "disable" inflation in order to exclude the need for action later on.
At 3.3 percent, the inflation rate reached a 12-year record in Germany in November; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
The rise in inflation in the eurozone is due to increased food and energy prices.
The MATIF wheat quotes increased by 88 percent, and the price for soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
Food oil and dairy products also experienced significant inflation in 2007.
The world market price for crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached almost 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 percent in 2008, but it is expected to fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3-percent inflation rate, but estimate the annual average rate at 2.1 per cent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to reduce interest rates twice.
Gallup orts government crisis
After a long period of stagnation, the number of Fidesz sympathizers has grown considerably until the beginning of December. For the first time since 2002, the party has the largest base camp, while, according to Gallup, approval for the Socialists has reached an unprecedented low of 13 percent.
The difference among party loyal voters is clear thanks to the high determination of the opposition supporters: more than two thirds (71 percent) are opposed to one fifth (20 percent) approval for the MSZP.
According to the survey, MDF and SZDSZ are under the parliamentary entry barrier: they reach two percent in the total population.
The number of party voters has grown by one percent in both camps.
Compared to the last low point, the general economic sentiment has continued to deteriorate - never before has the proportion of those who regard the country's economic situation as "very bad" been so high (41 percent), while a further 46 percent consider it "pretty bad."
According to more hopeful prospects in spring and summer, families again view the change in their financial situation as more pessimistic.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects a further deterioration of the situation; only one tenth expects an improvement.
A Gallup survey conducted in December revealed that 71% of respondents - a historic high - assessed the Prime Minister's work as "more bad than right."
Thirteen percent of respondents have great confidence or confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány in general, while the percentage of supporters for Viktor Orbán is 38 percent.
Around 54% do not trust the head of government at all, compared with 27% distrust of the party leader of Fidesz.
