After the unrest last October, 35% said that the government and the head of government would remain, today this figure is only 20%, while the relative majority (33 percent) sees the solution only in new elections.
Asked about their interest in the referendum, 60 percent replied that they would participate "with certainty," and a further 20% would give their vote "probably."
By way of comparison, if the parliamentary elections were to take place this Sunday, only 55 percent would go "with certainty" to the urns, a further 15% consider their participation to be "probable." Given these tendencies, the result of the referendum would be foreseeable.
74% would vote against tuition fees, 79% against the practice fee, and 84% against the hospital allowance.
Moved to the group of participants in the referendum "with certainty" the shares of opponents of study, practice and hospital fees would be even 81, 84, or 89 percent.
