In many places disinfectants are saved
This year, more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to improper use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in the hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds, the overcrowding of the staff - all factors that are not conducive to the containment of the infections, according to the chief physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of János Hospital, MRSA infection has recently been diagnosed.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, there was already a similar infection here.
The injury of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but a short time later the man had to return with an MRSA infection. An important operation could not be performed since then because of the bacterium, which is still in the patient's body.
By 10 December of this year, hospital infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to Karolina Böröcz, the leading physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have certainly been registered in hospitals, but the dark figure is likely to be higher.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacilline.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of the people in its nose without causing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as sore throat, tonsillitis, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the drugs are used too high or improperly, the well-responding bacteria produce antibiotic-resistant, which rapidly spread in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with a weakened or permanently poorly functioning immune system, but also in older patients or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause severe infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János hospital, MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of everyday hospital life.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi warned - MRSA does not exist only where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nurses wear rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment," says Tibor Nyulasi.
When they are admitted to the hospital, the patients are examined for MRSA, but infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is too rare
The majority of MRSA-induced infections in hospitals could be avoided, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavourable for the control of the emergence or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs predominantly in hospitals and nursing homes, the hospitals should examine the patients and isolate MRSA infected immediately.
In Hungarian hospitals, however, microbiological sampling is not practised so frequently.
Not least because there are no subsidies from the state health insurance fund for this study.
Most cases therefore only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the Epidemiology Center.
There are strict recommendations from the European Union on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and diseases in Hungary.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological investigations are necessary to prevent resistance to the drug, but this directive is not always respected by hospitals.
According to Karolina Böröcz, microbiological sampling is even rarer among outpatient patients or patients in basic care.
Saving of disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to the other by nurses.
It is precisely for this reason that hand washing or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also significant shortcomings in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient in the home hospitals.
The rooms are often overcrowded, the beds close to each other, although there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them from an epidemiological point of view.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately, it happens in the financially less well placed hospitals, that with disinfectants is saved, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that favor the emergence of infections.
Such infections are proven to be far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped, where these protective measures are observed, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Government programme against MRSA
Getting to grips with MRSA infections causes the health insurance companies enormous costs, so they are fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government program.
After first signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the tendency of MRSA infections in England is decreasing.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared the prevention of the emergence of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals as one of its priorities.
