A further EUR 400 million for infrastructure
Minister of Finance János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three loan agreements in Budapest on Friday totalling EUR 400 million, which will be used to finance education, transport and environmental infrastructure and the energy sector.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a EUR 300 million framework for the financing of transport and environmental projects implemented by the Cohesion Fund. The loan agreement for EUR 100 million was signed earlier and the current agreement concerns the use of the EUR 200 million lent.
The sum of EUR 150 million agreed in the loan agreement will also be devoted to the budget financing of educational projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for this purpose for Hungary, and the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be decided later in the context of the extension of the credit agreement.
In the field of innovation, the contracting parties have signed an agreement of EUR 50 million, which will mainly be used in research and development programmes at the University of Debrecen.
During the meeting, the metro line 4 was also discussed.
It was agreed that once Hungary clarified the details of the subway financing with the EU, the original contract and possible modifications would be discussed again.
According to János Veres, this would be possible in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects worth EUR 8.4 billion in Hungary.
The loan rates are EURIBOR-linked, the loan is made available by the EIB with a delay of 8 years, free of commission.
Bulgaria, the EU's real estate paradise
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - all of Europe looks closely at the Balkan state that was previously rarely mentioned.
What, where, and who buys the EU's cheapest market, but it is rapidly becoming more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most sought-after place for real estate purchases in Eastern Europe, with cheap ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Between the mountains the regions Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, by the sea Albena, the "Gold Coast," the "Sun Coast," and the historic towns Sozopol and Nessebar the racers, however, real estate around Kavarna and Balcik are also more and more in demand.
According to Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, the interior of the country will attract investors sooner or later, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and also the extremely favorable area of Russian has more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers tempting offers - commercial and office space offers highest returns.
Bulgaria is on the best way to become one of the most attractive European golfer paradises, and thus attract tourists in the other two seasons in addition to the summer and winter seasons.
For this reason, prospective investors are already buying in a large-scale way, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who purchase real estate in Bulgaria also seek to change their way of life.
Most buyers are English, but there are also interested parties from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while there are mainly Russian buyers in the Black Sea and in the ski resorts.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgy Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle, either buy revitalized properties by 50-100,000 euros, or run-down houses by 5-15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connectivity and accessibility as well as communication possibilities are important, but also the proximity to a big city, shops and doctors are crucial for the buyers.
The second category includes those who are looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed among the Top Ten holiday destinations of the Germans in December).
The third group consists of business people who invest with the aim of a medium- to long-term increase in value.
Real estate in the capital, however, is constantly becoming more expensive due to ever-increasing demand.
Within the EU, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria, but over the past five years there has been an annual increase of 21 percent.
The inflation rate in real estate prices far exceeds the rise in salaries.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percent
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue by the ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries will discuss the Bali Roadmap, which sets out the post-2012 emission reduction measures, i.e. the end of the Kyoto Protocol.
There is currently a heated debate between industrialised and developing countries.
The US has already signaled that they do not want to negotiate concrete figures, but they would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major issue at the conference is whether the industrialised countries are prepared to support developing countries, in addition to reducing emissions, both financially and technologically.
An agreement has also been reached on support for developing countries.
The adjustment fund under the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member Council, expected at the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as can be seen in the "Piac és Profit."
Hungary six percent
On behalf of Hungary, Environment Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate action and to achieve a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said that the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (as measured by 1990 levels) regardless of whether the "A post-2012 agreement" would be successful or not. The Union would even be prepared to commit itself to a 30% reduction if other major industrialised countries in the world, or developing countries, were also willing to fulfil their commitments in a strong and responsible manner.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the objective of the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU had already committed itself to a decrease of 8% with its then 15 member states.
The target for Hungary is a 6% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions compared to 1985-87 - a requirement that the country will certainly meet, as can be seen in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The deployment is high on Bali - after all, the long-term international climate agreement has to be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly only come into force after 2012. In this case, the reduction plans set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a renewed international emissions reduction system, whose importance was also highlighted by the IPCC, the international scientific climate change committee of the UN, which was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize.
This would delay the emission reduction, and raising the Earth's average temperature by more than 2°C would be inevitable, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
British Army advertises on YouTube
British Army units have published footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan in order to increase popularity on the video portal.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) discovered YouTube for itself: Special Forces stationed in Afghanistan have been broadcasting videos of Taliban-led operations since March 2006, reports the BBC.
The photos shot with miniature cameras mounted on helmets are controlled at the Air Force Base in Kandahar and then sent to London, where they are placed on the Internet.
Political message inevitable
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such photos, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defense was registered under Defence Headquarters in spring 2007 to publish videos of Iraqi and Afghan operations, but also the British Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Commonwealth Office) and the Iraq-based international peacekeeping forces (MNFI) have their own YouTube channels.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force has published the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and, as the Ministry of Defense says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual goals of foreign operations.
According to defense expert Gordon Mackenzie of the BBC, propaganda published in this way is almost free of charge compared to conventional television commercials, but these videos always carry a certain amount of political message, as they confirm the existence of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
Americans advertise with game
But the army must also fight against amateur shots, which, in addition to the carefully edited, censored shots, also make it into the net - such as those that show the death of the soldiers: in the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, at most, the losses are discussed, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
By the way, numerous videos of the war scenes in Iraq and Afghanistan have already been loaded onto the platform, but this "genre" has only recently been discovered by the British.
The Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the free downloadable shooting game "Americas Army," in which the player can slip into the soldier's skin as part of a more or less life-scattered simulation.
