Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases State Risk
In the opinion of the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guards, founded this August with the support of the "Movement for a Better Hungary," have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several respects.
Among other things, the Institute's "Risk Warning Report" states that, in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is "the intensification of the existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy population in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic conflicts in the short term."
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is probably aimed at the provocation of such an argument, says the research institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure on the part of political leaders: "People in public life have left the discussion of the Roma issue to representatives of radical political groups who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungary conflict."
It is believed that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, promote limbs, and increase the likelihood of violent confrontations.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least thanks to the enormous attention of the domestic and foreign media, "have seriously damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of confidence in stability and democratic maturity."
We remember that since autumn 2006 the reorganisation of radical and extreme right groups in Hungary has been on the upswing, so that since summer 2007 several organisations called "national self-defense association" have been founded.
"These groups are in common that they define themselves as civil organisations, while they openly boast about preparing their members for - sometimes armed - defense tasks (catastrophe protection, national defense, defense), citing the inability of the police, the army, or the state itself," they said.
And further, all this happens according to the method that attempts to disguise various political aspirations as a bourgeois initiative, based on the political and party disgruntledness of the population.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of the association are therefore not merely aimed at circumventing legal hurdles that may arise as a result of the registration at court - it is also a political strategy.
As can be seen from the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk-enhancing factor for relations with neighbouring countries.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited as a potential source of danger in several neighbouring countries, as some ultranationalist politicians in certain neighbouring countries see the emergence of the Hungarian Guard as a confirmation of its own anti-Hungary policy.
All of this has an impact on the political stability of the region," he said.
From the point of view of the research institute, the founding of the Hungarian Guard is not a single phenomenon in Central Eastern Europe, so the political risk for the entire region has grown.
As reported, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are comparable to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, which was announced by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU) in August 2007.
In the background to the emergence of the Bulgarian Guard were the Roma mass riots that took place in a district of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU has taken the incidents immediately as the reason for the formation of the National Guard, with the argument that the aim of the organization is "national protection."
