Holidays are not everywhere Holidays
In Hungary, holidays are regulated by law, so that the practice of redisposing the working days around the holidays has now established itself, but the coming year brings us fewer such days.
In the EU and America, too, the term "holiday" means something else.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between state holidays and work-free days.
Working days are mostly church holidays, or are associated with significant historical events.
For example, we are also celebrating New Year: both the last day of the old and the first day of the new year are work-free days - the latter alone so that the New Year's Eve celebrations can rest.
All year round, we have fourteen holidays.
The state holidays are March 15, commemorating the revolution of 1848 and October 23, commemorating the revolution of 1956.
On August 20th, the foundation of the state, on May 1st the work is celebrated, on November 1st and 2nd we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each at Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our national, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "working day relocation" has proven itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on Saturdays before, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is ultimately to be worked out, is laid down for long years by the Minister of Labour in a separate regulation.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and employees, public employees and civil servants.
Only companies and institutions in which the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on the holidays, are excluded.
In this case, the work regulations are only somewhat confused by the holidays at the end of the year: from 24 December, life in this country will remain formally standing, since most take time compensation for the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve, or the holiday reserved for this purpose.
Next year there will be more holidays in the middle of the week, or at the end of the week, so that there will be fewer changes in working days than this year.
The calendar is first "turned upside down" around the day of work, so that people can stay at home for four days at a time.
Saturday, April 26th will be a working day so that Friday, May 2nd can be a day of rest.
The second repositioning is related to the holiday on October 23rd: on Saturday, October 18th, Friday, October 24th will have to be worked on in advance.
The end of the year, however, will be completely marked by the holidays, after everything will lie and stop from December 24, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
Six deterrent little things to annoy workmates
E-mails that we forget to send, voice messages that we never receive - harmless lies that we don't notice anymore: They bring "color" into everyday life at work.
