Tips.
"Sorry, I forgot to tell you someone from the marketing department called," says a colleague.
That you missed a meeting?
At best, you regret it and try to make up for it by perhaps calling the marketing department and repentantly admitting that you would have forgotten to align the message (this is the less common method).
Most of the time, it's done with an apology.
Before you get involved in embarrassing excuses, you should think about how to give your colleagues truly unpleasant moments and try to avoid these situations consciously.
Something you don't own?
There's hardly anything more annoying than reaching for a document, office supplies, or the phone, but it's not there.
Yesterday the stapler was still on the desk - this morning it's gone?
Or is the lost ballpoint pen discovered on a colleague's desk?
Without asking, you should not borrow anything from colleagues, because they are rightly upset when they find that something has gone away.
So, don't put any envelopes or post-it in your pocket from the office, because it could hit you yourself: no more, if you need it urgently.
Gossing about colleagues' private lives?
There is no effective way to stop a gossip that has already been put into the world.
Who did what with who?
Where and why?
If possible, you should not tie the information (or guesses) about the personal life of colleagues to everyone's nose!
And if someone opens up and reveals his inner secret to us, we should not abuse that trust!
It is best to remain silent like a grave, rather than align the one who is not present, even if others know about the problems of the colleague.
Reported sick for no reason?
When you call the office to report sick on the basis of tormenting headaches, because you feel uncomfortable right now, or just want to rest, you should be aware of one thing: Your own work, unstoppable tasks, projects with fixed appointments must now be done by your colleagues instead of yourself.
So don't play bad with your colleagues!
If you already know the day before that you won't make it to the office the next day, or that something could come up, which is why you have to stay at home, you should report it in time, so that neither the colleagues nor the boss are unexpectedly confronted with the absence.
Sum, giggles, phone calls
One is in depth in his work, but is suddenly disturbed by the loud giggle of the colleagues?
Wouldn't you listen to a phone call that you shouldn't have heard?
One should not annoy colleagues with humming, singing, loud conversations (which one leads over their heads), bragging, constant scolding or nagging.
All of this can be very disturbing, even if they are not engrossed in a task (writing, planning, organizing).
Are the others always to blame?
If a project is not completed on time, you have forgotten to send an important letter or important messages, you should not look for the guilt of your forgetfulness with others!
If possible, you should not talk about the chaos in the office or the noisy colleagues!
It is best to admit your mistakes and apologize if others were affected!
The question of how to make up for the mistake, or how to make up for what is missing, is all too appropriate!
In the office - a feeling like home?
Training pants and slapping: Comfortable for home, but didn't lose anything in the office!
Not even then should you dress so casually, if the workplace would actually allow it!
Just don't get too sloppy - you should respect both your colleagues and yourself to the extent that you dress accordingly in the office - if desired, also pretty and elegant!
