With these songs the singer György Ligeti, who lives in England and works with the band "The Puzzle," introduced himself at the premiere in the Millenáris.
A song from the album even made it to the radio hit - the mr2 Petőfi, which has been broadcasting pop music since the very latest from early to late, has gradually set the earworm for the listeners with the number "Wings of Love," which was recorded with the help of six domestic singers ("Underground Divas").
So everything's all right (?).
The hvg.hu asked Balázs Zságer.
hvg.hu: This new hit raises the question: To what extent is your music reserved for a certain layer?
Balázs Zságer: The term "shift music" doesn't mean much to me.
In my opinion, there are two boxes in pop music, not mainstream and underground, or alternative and pop, but commercial and honest.
Even the so-called alternative or underground music can be shallow and meaningless, but in the same way they can only be produced for sale, which makes them commercial music.
Also a good pop number can arise from an honest motive.
The listener's willingness to record also works on this principle, independently of languages and national borders.
hvg.hu: Do you see a difference in the openness of the Hungarian and foreign audiences to your music?
B. Zs.: Pop music has a greater tradition abroad, especially west of us.
Not only teenagers or Twens go to concerts, but also the older audience.
They follow the trends in pop music that happen around them much more attentively, because they also think they are part of contemporary culture.
hvg.hu: What role does the audience play in your work?
Does it matter who, where, how many listen to your music?
B. Zs.: Of course, it's a good feeling to see that more and more of our concerts are coming.
But we never composed for the market.
With us the music does not arise to serve a purpose, but for a certain reason.
The role of the audience is usually noticeable in the concerts, where there is already a mutual interaction, but in turn there are only in the incomprehensible changes of the moment.
Nevertheless, I noticed one thing: if you want to do it right, you are no longer interesting.
hvg.hu: How far would you like to follow the example of Yonderboi?
He is on his way as a soloist and has built his career in the West.
B. Zs.: We don't really go our way, let alone try to interpret this into our music.
We see ourselves more as a team player who trusts in the musical presence of the other and lets them unfold.
At first, of course, comparisons of our work with Yonderboi's were inevitable, as several of us came out of his band and took a different path.
hvg.hu: In the charts of mr2 Petőfi, "Wings of Love" is the top priority.
Many have only heard the name Zagar in connection with this number.
Was the opening consciously staged with a slightly more popular style towards a wider audience?
B. Zs.: We had no plans to write a hit, which was then to hold as a drawhorse for the album.
This song is about more.
It was intended as the finale of the album, with which we wanted to dissolve the sound orgy and the somewhat more difficult themes.
hvg.hu: How did you choose the six singers?
Why they, what was the guiding principle?
B. Zs.: The basic idea was to make a gospel-like choir.
Then came the idea of putting together the choir from gifted soloists of the local music scene.
This is how the six-member choir was created - that is, Sena, Edina Kutzora, Judie Jay, Bori Péterfy, Enikő Hodosi [Neo], Juci Németh - which we later christened "Underground Divas."
hvg.hu: Did you want the song the same way, or did the girls co-create it?
B. Zs.: The number was already longer in the instrumental version, but when the material was ready for the album, we thought that this number still "needs something."
The chord sequence has formally demanded a vocal voice.
I sang the melody the same night, later they learned the girls.
It all came virtually immediately and frighteningly spontaneous.
I remember I was pretty electrified back then, but it was the divas that needed it.
With my voice alone, the song would never have become so strong.
hvg.hu: Both on the record and at the concert, however, one had the impression that the girls were in the background.
There is no solo part (apart from the short solo by Judy Jay), they have no role of their own, sing together completely and are not louder than the music, so their singing is not only accompanied by the music.
They were also on stage.
Is it on purpose?
B.Zs.: The fact that they were standing behind was because of purely technical problems.
However, we deliberately did not want to send them solo roles.
The number is also about forgetting one's ego a little, forgetting who came from where and where to go, we just let these particular wings, the wings of love lift us up.
I would like others to feel the euphoric state we felt when the song was made.
hvg.hu: Which was the most elaborate song?
B. Zs.: In musical work, there was actually no one at all, there were more difficult tasks when mixing.
For example, in "Dorian Gray's Dilemma," where I play on a concert piano, or in "Rock'n'Roll Goes To The Girls," where the groove didn't want to work any longer, but gradually everything has teamed up like a puzzle.
hvg.hu: What is your favorite number from the new album?
B. Zs.: This is constantly changing with the concerts and now that I have "released" the album.
Currently it is "Prophet Is A Fool," "Escape From The Earth" and the number "Never The Same."
