Banks want to cope with crisis
The US Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Great Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight together against the crisis in the financial markets.
More than $100 billion will reach the currency markets through auctions.
At these auctions, the banks auction interest rates at which they are willing to borrow each other's money.
For example, the American Fed is sending $40 billion to auction, and another 24 is loosening it for the European and Swiss Central Banks.
After the attacks of September 11th, it is the first time that the central banks of the individual states agree on such a coordinated approach to countering or mitigating the consequences of a financial crisis.
"This step is intended to eliminate the biggest difficulties of the economy, i.e. the increasing lack of freely available capital that banks can lend," wrote in a report for its customers Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group.
"The coordinated action of the central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the US from 65% to about 50%," added Baumohl in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to unserviced loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts expect further billions of losses.
" Central banks must have been really afraid of what can still be done when they decided to do so, " said ABN Amro's chief economist, Kieran Davies.
"It looks like the situation is really bad," he continued.
Central banks are concerned that if the banks themselves have difficult access to bonds, loans will also become more expensive for their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the American economy into a recession, possibly affecting economic growth around the world.
The central banks decided to do so after they failed to lower the so-called LIBOR, the London interbank rate used to lend money between banks.
This means that banks were constantly afraid of borrowing money from each other, despite the fact that the US, Canadian and UK central banks had lowered their interest rates several times during the autumn.
"This will have the same effect as a further lowering of interest rates," said Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting of the agency Reuters.
Some analysts believe that this step of central banks is helping to heat up the crisis because it does not solve the fundamental problem, namely the case of the real estate market in the US.
