Cuba - most beautiful island of the Caribbean
For visitors, it is really an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your vacation will come true if you just choose the right one.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a sea that is quiet like a pond.
Palm trees and All Inclusive with waiters that offer pizza, ice cream and beguiling cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean you will find this in abundance.
But only on one island you will find much more, and this island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Great Antilles.
At the time of the Spaniards, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place a human eye has ever seen.
Havana once became a camp or transit camp of treasures that the Spaniards had robbed in America and then transported to Europe.
And then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built at the end of the 20th century.
One of the chiefs of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, had it built because everything that was considered a crime in the US (especially during prohibition) was welcomed and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
==References====External links==
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rise buildings grew, and across the wide boulevards cars drove, which were among the cult symbols of the fifties of the last century.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Cojímar he had his yacht.
On the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio, stars of the show business and politicians from all over America left their signatures.
And today?
You can also leave your autograph on the walls of the Havana Bodeguita.
At the bar at the Hotel Nacional you can mix cocktails as you wish.
And the cult of the fifties still drive around in Havana, because the once imported Shigulis and Fiats have long since fallen apart in the salty and damp air.
Havana, especially its oldest part, may have come down badly, but nowhere around you can find as many wonderful colonial sights as just here.
Other places are being cleaned out, such as Trinidad.
In view of the urgent need for money from tourism, there was a green light for this development.
Over the past fifteen years, new hotels have been created not only in Havana, but also in Varadero, on the coast of Holguín Province and also on islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a marl that is unique in the world and especially attracts railway lovers.
The sugar cane from remote plantations brought steam and diesel-powered narrow gauges to the sugar factories.
Her fleet has not been renewed for decades, and so you can see cute and fully functioning locomotives, whose contemporaries are standing somewhere else in the museum.
Excursion destinations
The majority of visitors to Cuba do not leave out the most important places.
So you don't have to write in detail about Varadero or Havana anymore.
It remains to be mentioned that there is a museum in Hemingway's already mentioned estate, the visit of which should not be missed by anyone who likes this writer.
The Viñales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on limestone soil.
The mogotas, limestone hills and rocks, rise steeply from the bottom of the valley, in their cavities fertile soil accumulates, through which also weathered rock areas are covered by dense vegetation.
This valley is where perhaps the best Cuban tobacco is grown.
In its final form, you can meet him when you visit one of Havana's cigar factories.
It may also seem interesting to some that the Chilean episode of the television series "Major Zeman" was filmed there.
Trinidad
An ancient city that was founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
Glory and wealth brought her the trade in slaves and sugar.
The wealth embodied itself in the beautiful beauty of the small town.
The Spanish colonial architecture, strongly influenced by the later French settlers, has hardly changed for four hundred years.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is such a remote place that there was still no road there in the fifties of the last century that would have connected the area to the rest of the country.
This isolation helped to keep it unnoticed.
Nothing was built there, but therefore nothing was torn down, everyone was glad that he had a roof over his head.
If you have more than one afternoon for Trinidad, it is worth looking at interesting places in the area, such as the beach Playa Ancón or the "valley of sugar factories."
In the evening you should then go to the Casa de la Música, which is lively after the darkness, and where the music does not remain silent until the morning.
Baracoa
Some call this town the most beautiful of the island in eastern Cuba.
Certainly this view is also influenced by the way there.
Both roads, which lead from Guantánamo there, have to overcome high and rugged mountains and run through a landscape that is hardly touched by human intervention.
This eastern outpost of Cuba was included by UNESCO in its World Heritage List, thanks to its pristine nature.
There the best chocolate is produced, in the church you can see the Cross of Columbus (actually it was created about a hundred years after the voyages of Columbus), and from the hill where the former castle, the current Hotel El Castillo, stands, you can see several table mountains, of which El Yunque is the most famous.
About coffee, rum, cigars, the Sierra Maestra mountains, the Bay of Pigs and the island of Isla de Pinos, about the Tropicana cabaret, the shrine of the Cuban patroness Caridad del Cobre, about the Santeria, an African religion to which the descendants of slaves profess, about all this one could write many pages.
But, as they say, look better with your own eyes.
