Astronaut Scott Parazynski and his comrades from the crew of the International Space Station (ISS) will have taken more than seven hours in space to carry out the spectacular repair of a defective solar collector indispensable for the continuation of scientific work on the station.
A daring exit that has achieved several records due to its duration, the removal of habitable modules, the speed with which it was organized, and the tools made by the astronauts to carry out the repair.
The problem arose on Wednesday, when the astronauts had unloaded the Harmony module from the Discovery space shuttle, a large cylinder-shaped part that is soon to take up the European and Japanese scientific laboratories.
