The Congress approved the MIFID Directive, which entered into force on 1 November.
Parallel to the parliamentary drafting, which ended today with the Congress resolution in the Senate on the additional/amendments to the project, the government published the provisions arising from the new law with the intention of enabling the entry into force of both regulations by the end of the year.
The representatives of the various companies unanimously praised the efforts of Congress and Senate members, who in their negotiations and votes had the aim of establishing the best possible regulation that ensures investor safety and regulates individual entrepreneurial activities in order to guarantee a generally efficient market activity.
In addition to modernising the financial markets, the MIFID, which is redefining the securities services code, is pursuing an improvement in investor protection, an increase in the control entitlement of the Spanish Securities Commission (CNMV) and the promotion of cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
The new Directive allows for financial advice to be provided to both specialised firms and natural or legal persons and also contributes to the establishment of new financial services companies (ESIS), the consultancy companies which are associated with the investment and brokerage companies of securities.
It also extends the number of financial transaction execution systems, adding multilateral securities business systems and trading order internationalisation systems to regulated securities markets, which would eventually enter into competition with current economic actors.
The law obliges investment companies to disclose the priorities of their company profile, the confrontation and the forms of dealing with risks on the market and to register all the projects carried out in order to facilitate the CNMV's control task.
