New fears about gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute is disappearing between Ukraine and Russia, which increases the risk of Russian exports being affected by fuel to Western Europe.
Most of Russia's gas exports to the European Union (EU) are led by Ukraine and every dispute between the two nations is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge Russia higher transit charges.
A previous conflict between the two states last year reduced deliveries to the EU countries.
The recent dispute between Kiev and Moscow occurs at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine has to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine must be charged more, as the Group has agreed to pay up to 50% in addition for natural gas from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for imports of Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in talks," said the Minister of Economy of Ukraine Anatoli Kinakh of the news agency Reuters.
"The changing gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit charges [to Western Europe] via Ukraine."
In the last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom reduced deliveries to Ukraine.
This resulted in a case of exports to Western Europe, which drastically increased prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the world's largest gas reserves, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
The result is that Gazprom complements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS "must control foreign workers"
The Scottish State Health Service must improve controls on criminal records for workers from outside Europe, said one member of the control body.
The recommendation of the Chief Financial Controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor was brought in Scotland in connection with the attack on Glasgow airport in June.
Black also expressed concern that the Scottish State Health Service did not have any precise ideas about the number of its foreign employees.
But his report pointed out that other important checks were carried out correctly in a sample of five health authorities.
The chief financial controller investigated personnel recruited outside the countries of the European Economic Area as a result of the attack on Glasgow airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a SUV was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video broadcast at Old Bailey in October, and was charged in connection with the alleged car bomb attack in Britain.
It is expected that the State Health Service will carry out checks prior to the recruitment of foreign employees to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorization to work in the UK.
Although health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to review criminal records, the Agency does not have jurisdiction to obtain such information outside the UK.
The main auditor's report now states, among other recommendations, that the Executive Board should take up guidelines of the criminal record statement, which helps employers with controls in different countries.
"Although we have found evidence of these controls in some personnel records, these have not been routinely carried out," the report noted.
Black said that the Scottish health authorities would follow their investigative guidelines to a large extent before hiring, but added: "Our report identifies areas where the system can be improved to ensure that accurate information on the number of foreign health service staff is available."
BMA Scotland Chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that investigations prior to hiring potential NHS employees would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks.
"The report states that current pre-selection tests by the NHS Scotland work well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will provide," he said.
The Scottish health authorities say that they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the vast majority of them doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number was likely to be higher, also because the board of directors had problems identifying those employees who were on leave indefinitely.
The investigation also found that established control procedures by NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian were predominantly observed.
These include passport, work permit, and qualification checks.
the Scottish Government is currently reviewing its policy and guidelines for pre-employment controls for foreign staff in the NHS.
The Secretary of Health Nicola Sturgeon said, "It was my concern to carry out this work in the face of the terrorist attack on Glasgow Airport."
It added that the Scottish Government, in conjunction with the health authorities, would take into account the recommendations of the report and ensure that the best practices would be reflected in updated guidelines on control investigations prior to the recruitment of all employees, including those from abroad, whose publication is planned next month.
