Venus is the hellish twin of the earth
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is more similar to the Earth than previously thought: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lightnings in the atmosphere and wind vortexes on the Poles, as they occur on Earth in winter.
For almost three decades, scientists have assumed that it flashes on Venus.
Now the European probe "Venus Express" has demonstrated - it detected electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere: The lightning on Venus shoots at an altitude of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California in Los Angeles in the science magazine "Nature."
According to the famous "prime soup theory," lightning has created life on Earth: thunderstorms are said to have stimulated reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: "If there was ever life there, it must have been in the very early history," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today there is hardly anything alive on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus may be the devil's twin of the earth, but it is a twin," said Russel.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, has taken such a completely different development, is the basic question of the Esa mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, as since the beginning of the nineties no probe had been on its way specifically to explore this planet.
According to the researchers, the latest research results, which are now presented in several "Nature" articles, not only underline the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
"They also show that the similarities of our neighbouring planet with the Earth are greater than initially assumed," the Esa informs.
In addition to the already known whirlwind at the North Pole, the researchers found a cloud strudel at the South Pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the earthly winter hemisphere, writes a research team led by Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is almost as large as 12,100 kilometres in diameter.
The planet, also known as the morning or evening star, orbits the sun in just under 225 days.
But it revolves much slower around itself: a Venus day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus hardly resembles Earth with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, scientists assume that both planets have been formed under very similar conditions.
On both of them, water accumulated, which remained on Earth in oceans, but on which Venus was lost to space.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed on Earth in carbonate rocks, it makes up the majority of the atmosphere on Venus.
