These aren't Warhol's boxes.
Those who combine the concepts of Sweden and wooden box think of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Isn't it?
Currently in Sweden fabricated wooden boxes cast dark shadows on Warhol's catalogue of works.
Most of the ninety-four Brillo boxes listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes of 1968, internal research at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm has now come to a sobering conclusion: the six "Brillo-Boxes," which the former museum director Pontus Hultén bequeathed to the Moderna Museet in 1995, are copies - and probably also the majority of the approximately one hundred other Brillo boxes of the "type Stockholm" that are circulating on the international art market.
The prehistory is nested, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard boxes of the "Brillo" soap powder.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 showed - with Warhol's consent - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: these were not from Warhol (for cost reasons) but were delivered directly from the Brillo Cartonage Factory.
They were not works of art, but their role models, mere exhibits.
At the same time, in 1968 Warhol probably granted permission to produce a few Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of about fifteen boxes, which at that time as authorized original Andy Warhol Brillo boxes with the name "type Stockholm" rightly entered into the art and auction history.
Some of them have achieved more than $100,000 at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that some hundred wooden boxes were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were not produced until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief conservator at the Moderna Museet, has investigated the six Brillo boxes in addition to the museum's own, three private Swedish owned ones, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their press plates were first primed and embellished, then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the press plate with a paint roll without primer - in addition, it is not an oil paint, but an acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes," says the director of Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
Already in July, the Authentication Board announced that it would investigate the "heavy accusations" raised in the case of soap powder boxes.
But since then, they have been shrouded in relentless silence.
Rebelling soldiers in Manila give up
In the Philippines, rebellious soldiers who had entrenched themselves in a hotel in Manila and demanded the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
He could not be responsible for bloodshed, said the leader Antonio Trillenes, who accused the president of corruption and electoral fraud, reporters in the hotel.
Government soldiers had previously stormed the hotel under tear gas.
The approximately two dozen soldiers had been entrenched in the building for hours.
About half of them were on trial on Thursday for a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillenes.
He used the trial to suddenly settle down with about 30 sympathizers.
The military policemen who were supposed to guard him had apparently run over to him and joined his mutiny.
